{"parse":{"title":"The Crying Boy","pageid":5760218,"revid":836624474,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p class=\"mw-empty-elt\">\n</p>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:242px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Bragolin_Crying_Boy.JPG\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/8/86/Bragolin_Crying_Boy.JPG/240px-Bragolin_Crying_Boy.JPG\" width=\"240\" height=\"303\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/8/86/Bragolin_Crying_Boy.JPG 1.5x\" data-file-width=\"288\" data-file-height=\"363\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Bragolin_Crying_Boy.JPG\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>The artist's signature <i>G Bragolin</i> is present in the top-right corner</div></div></div>\n<p><i><b>The Crying Boy</b></i> is a <a href=\"/wiki/Mass_production\" title=\"Mass production\">mass-produced</a> print of a painting by <a href=\"/wiki/Italy\" title=\"Italy\">Italian</a> painter <a href=\"/wiki/Giovanni_Bragolin\" title=\"Giovanni Bragolin\">Giovanni Bragolin</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Polidoro2012_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Polidoro2012-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> It was widely distributed from the 1950s onwards.\n</p><p>There are numerous alternative versions, all portraits of tearful young boys or girls.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Polidoro2012_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Polidoro2012-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> In addition to being widely known, certain <a href=\"/wiki/Urban_legend\" title=\"Urban legend\">urban legends</a> attribute a \"curse\" to the painting.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Curse\">Curse</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=The_Crying_Boy&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Curse\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>On 5 September 1985, the British <a href=\"/wiki/Tabloid_(newspaper_format)\" title=\"Tabloid (newspaper format)\">tabloid</a> newspaper <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Sun_(United_Kingdom)\" title=\"The Sun (United Kingdom)\">The Sun</a></i> reported that an Essex <a href=\"/wiki/Firefighter\" title=\"Firefighter\">firefighter</a> claimed that undamaged copies of the painting were frequently found amidst the ruins of burned houses.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Polidoro2012_1-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Polidoro2012-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> By the end of November, belief in the painting's curse was widespread enough that <i>The Sun</i> was organising mass <a href=\"/wiki/Bonfire\" title=\"Bonfire\">bonfires</a> of the paintings, sent in by readers.<sup id=\"cite_ref-sun-2010_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-sun-2010-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p><a href=\"/wiki/Steve_Punt\" title=\"Steve Punt\">Steve Punt</a>, a British writer and comedian, investigated the curse of the crying boy in a <a href=\"/wiki/BBC_Radio_4\" title=\"BBC Radio 4\">BBC Radio 4</a> production called <i><a href=\"/wiki/Punt_PI\" title=\"Punt PI\">Punt PI</a></i>. Although the format of the programmes are comic in nature, Punt researched the history of the Crying Boy painting.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> The conclusion reached by the programme, following testing at the <a href=\"/wiki/Building_Research_Establishment\" title=\"Building Research Establishment\">Building Research Establishment</a>, is that the prints were treated with a <a href=\"/wiki/Varnish\" title=\"Varnish\">varnish</a> containing <a href=\"/wiki/Fire_retardant\" title=\"Fire retardant\">fire retardant</a>, and that the string holding the painting to the wall would be the first to deteriorate, resulting in the painting landing face down on the floor and thus being protected, although no explanation was given as to why no other paintings were turning up unscathed. The picture was also mentioned in an episode about curses in the TV series <i><a href=\"/wiki/Weird_or_What%3F\" title=\"Weird or What?\">Weird or What?</a></i> in 2012.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=The_Crying_Boy&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Hands_Resist_Him\" title=\"The Hands Resist Him\">The Hands Resist Him</a></i>, also known as <i>The eBay Haunted Painting</i></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=The_Crying_Boy&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-Polidoro2012-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Polidoro2012_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Polidoro2012_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Polidoro2012_1-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Polidoro, Massimo (November/December 2012), \"Curse That Painting!\", <i>Skeptical Inquirer</i> <b>36</b> (6): 17\u201319</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-sun-2010-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-sun-2010_2-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Steve Punt, \"Solved: Curse of the Crying Boy; Comic\u2019s Obsession with Painting\", The Sun, 9 October 2010, p.8.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><i><a href=\"/wiki/Punt_PI\" title=\"Punt PI\">Punt PI</a>,</i>  <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00v697r\">Crying Boy episode</a> (programme broadcast Sat 9 Oct 2010, BBC Radio 4)</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.syfy.com/weirdorwhat/episodes/season/2/episode/204/curses\">Curses in Weird or What?</a> on <a href=\"/wiki/SyFy\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"SyFy\">SyFy</a></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw2183\nCached time: 20180913073926\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.048 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.067 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 233/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 835/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 197/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 12/40\nExpensive parser function count: 1/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 2000/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.008/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 810 KB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%   50.887      1 -total\n 39.54%   20.123      1 Template:Italic_title\n 28.91%   14.712      1 Template:Use_dmy_dates\n 23.69%   12.053      1 Template:Reflist\n 20.40%   10.380      1 Template:DMCA\n 16.93%    8.614      1 Template:Dated_maintenance_category\n 10.65%    5.421      1 Template:FULLROOTPAGENAME\n  7.28%    3.706      1 Template:Ns_has_subpages\n  4.49%    2.283      1 Template:Main_other\n-->\n\n<!-- Saved in parser cache with key enwiki:pcache:idhash:5760218-0!canonical and timestamp 20180913073925 and revision id 836624474\n -->\n</div>"},"langlinks":[{"lang":"ar","u